Jump Directly to U-IT Functional Needs and U-IT Solutions

 

DTPAT AS AN A-IT SOLUTION:

With the increasing need to remove all Unauthorized Information Technology (U-IT) from the DFAS network, the migration of U-IT to an Authorized IT (A-IT) environment is becoming more apparent and necessary. The migration of ACL applications to the DFAS Tactical Process Analysis Tool (DTPAT) Server is one of the A-IT solutions available for those looking to move their processes to an Authority to Operate (ATO) Boundary.

 

DTPAT SERVER USED FOR:

Audit Command Language (ACL) Applications and Processes used for data reconciliation and analysis.

 

DTPAT SERVER A GOOD FIT?

The DTPAT Server is the Galvanize ACL Analytics Exchange (AX) Server that is used to host all ACL collections and processes. By migrating to the DTPAT Server, current U-IT (Unauthorized Information Technology) ACL applications can be registered as A-IT under IT (Information Technology) guidance and standards. The DTPAT Server is a viable ACL A-IT solution as it ensures all potential ACL applications fall within the ATO Boundary and remain compliant while on the server. The DTPAT Server environment is responsible for the documentation of ACL Collections to enable maximizing DTPAT performance standards to align with the DFAS strategic priorities of Investing in People, Modernize the Business Environment, Enhance Performance, and Strengthen Customer Partnerships.

 

When evaluating migrating from Desktop ACL to the ACL server (DTPAT), consider:

1. Is there a need to limit access to the code and protect it from change?

a. More specifically, should the application be locked down so it is limited to who can develop it and make authorized changes in accordance with DFAS change management policies?

2. Is there a need for segregation of duties?

a. ACL Server (DTPAT) projects enable the use of Active Directory (AD) groups to lock down types of access to shared folders and tasks/roles for running projects.

3. Is there a need for a System Agreement for the data/connection being used?

a. If any data sources are being accessed outside of the team’s ownership, a system agreement is most likely needed between all the parties to detail how the data is accessed, identify data types (PII, Financial Institutional data), what is done with the data, and responsibilities of parties for providing and accessing the data, as well as protection of data

4. Is there a need for the project to be automated to execute on a schedule?

a. ACL Server (DTPAT) projects can be set up to run on regular schedules using automation, while also providing the means to run on-demand as well.

5. Is there a need for multiple users to have the ability to run the project? For example:

a. If someone is on leave and a backup needs to run the project.

b. If more than one person in the office has responsibilities and needs to have access to run on-demand to review for changes/updates since the project was last executed

6. Is there a need for the project and the end products to be used as an audit artifact?

a. ACL Server (DTPAT) projects provide enhanced auditing capabilities provided by the DTPAT team which includes daily reporting of user accounts, activities, and job execution

7. Is there a need to archive the imported data, analytic results, and reports?

a. All originally imported and un-manipulated source data can be archived for audit purposes, and protected from unauthorized access

b. Analytic results and reports can be archived as well, and protected from unauthorized access

 

CAPABILITIES INCLUDE:

1. DTPAT is an authorized IT solution

· DTPAT has an ATO and has been vetted to be an approved IT solution

· ACL collections included on the DTPAT server would fall within this ATO boundary, and therefore would not require individual, or separate, ATOs, for each ACL collection

2. Audit traceability

· The server logs and project logs increase visibility to project runs and analysis’

· The DTPAT server enables the use of Active Directory (AD) groups to lock down types of access to shared network folders and tasks/roles for running projects

3. Increased speed of project runs

· Moving to the server increases the speed of projects on the server compared to ACL Desktop, especially if the project is normally run from a shared drive

4. Project Scheduling - completing without manual intervention

· Projects that are routine and can be placed on a schedule can be automated to run at a certain time and day on a schedule, saving time for users

5. Multiple users can access/run the project and view the results

· The DTPAT server has a web client that allows many users to access and run projects

6. Secured code

· While the code is in Production, users cannot modify code

7. System Interfaces

· The DTPAT server can automate file retrievals and send reports to systems.

 

LIMITATIONS INCLUDE:

· ACL does not manipulate raw data or make any changes to it – no direct data input

· No access by external DFAS users

· Currently, customers are expected to learn ACL scripting and take ownership of development with our team’s support

· No direct digital signature abilities

· Not a ticketing system/help desk solution

· Data Refresh with real-time data requires ad-hoc or scheduled running of jobs

· DTPAT cannot connect to SharePoint

· Segregation of Duties requires 4 or more users per collection

 

DTPAT SERVER PROCESS:

The process of migrating an ACL tool to the DTPAT Server involves working with different teams, which includes the Hosting Intake team, ESS Business Capability and Process Modeling (BC&PM) team, and the DTPAT Server team. The teams all work together to guide, develop, and document the process of the ACL migration. Below are the following steps to take when a user identifies the need to migrate a U-IT application to the DTPAT Server:

1. Citizen Developer begins taking necessary ACL training available on the DFAS SharePoint Page located here: https://dfasportal.dfas.mil/ddss/eps/Pages/ACLAnalytics.aspx

2. Citizen Developer identifies need to migrate a new desktop ACL tool to the DTPAT server and accesses the necessary DTPAT ACL Hosting Intake Form on the DFAS ACL CoP SharePoint Page here: https://dfasportal.dfas.mil/sites/c35/ACL_COP/SitePages/Home.aspx, or emails dfas.indianapolis-in.zte.list.dtpat-svr-hosting@mail.mil

3. Once the ACL Hosting Intake document is completed, a Hosting Intake Meeting is scheduled with the Hosting Intake team and the DTPAT Server Team to identify if the requesting ACL tool will be a good fit within DTPAT

4. Preliminary CCB (Configuration Control Board) meeting takes place with all functional and technical representatives to coordinate efforts and clearly define expectations with all necessary stakeholders

5. Citizen Developer presents their ACL application during the quarterly CCB Charter to be voted on by voting members of the DTPAT CCB made up of government personnel

6. Upon receiving a quorum of 4 votes for the approval of the Server Request or Server Change Request of the ACL tool, the migration process begins

Citizen Developer owns the ACL project on their desktop and makes required changes to scripts throughout the process to standardize and prepare for the DTPAT Server

7. Throughout the migration process, the DTPAT Server Team works with the Customer to assist with moving their ACL application from Desktop to the Development Server, to the Test, and releasing to the Production Server.

 

U-IT FUNCTIONAL NEEDS AND A-IT SOLUTIONS

Existing U-IT applications within the operational areas across DFAS were evaluated for functional need requirements. Six major categories of functional needs were identified: Workload Management, Workflow, Ticketing, Data Reconciliation, Data Analytics, and Data Transformation.

The current five A-IT solutions (ACL (DTPAT) Server, Cognos, SharePoint, Oracle Apex, and Advana) provided scores to reflect the software’s ability to meet specific functional needs. Scores were obtained in three areas: capability, skillset, and coding. The scores are intended to serve as a guide during the process of exploring possible A-IT solutions. Higher scores indicated increased feasibility that the A-IT solution will be a suitable option to meet the functional needs.

 

 

 

HOW DO I GET MORE INFORMATION/ACL TRAINING?

Prior to migration to the DTPAT server, the Citizen Developer should have already created a working ACL desktop project or something that is mostly functional and taken the online training offered by Galvanize (available to all DFAS employees). The DTPAT team will then work one-on-one during the migration to help build the skillset into more advanced techniques where needed.

· All details about ACL and the initial process to begin migration inside of DFAS are found on this ePortal page:

· ACL Analytics (dfas.mil) https://dfasportal.dfas.mil/ddss/eps/Pages/ACLAnalytics.aspx

 

· Community of Practice page at DFAS for users to support each other during the migration process is located here:

· ACL-COP - Home (dfas.mil) https://dfasportal.dfas.mil/sites/c35/ACL_COP/SitePages/Home.aspx
